    p=11: P(p)=34816, S_P = -680, direct = -680, match = True
    p=19: P(p)=641536, S_P = -22554, direct = -22554, match = True

  k=11: P(p) = 1 + -55*p^1 + 330*p^2 + -462*p^3 + 165*p^4 + -11*p^5
    p=7: P(p)=68608, S_P = -201, direct = -201, match = True
    p=11: P(p)=68608, S_P = -335, direct = -335, match = True
    p=19: P(p)=-8784896, S_P = 77211, direct = 77211, match = True

======================================================================
Section 2: Interval eigenvalue sum S_I(k)
======================================================================

    mu_j = sum_{s=1}^m omega^{js} = (omega^j - omega^{j(m+1)}) / (1 - omega^j)

    For p = 3 mod 4, m = (p-1)/2, so m+1 = (p+1)/2.

    omega^{j(m+1)} = omega^{j(p+1)/2} = omega^{j/2} * omega^{jp/2}
                   = omega^{j/2} * (-1)^j  (since omega^{p/2} doesn't exist for odd p...)

    Actually, omega^{jp/2} = e^{2*pi*i*j*p/(2p)} = e^{pi*i*j} = (-1)^j.
    Wait, that's not right either. omega^{p/2} is not well-defined since p is odd.

    Let me use omega^{jm} = omega^{j(p-1)/2} instead.
    omega^{j(p-1)/2} = (omega^j)^{(p-1)/2} = e^{2*pi*i*j*(p-1)/(2p)}
                      = e^{pi*i*j} * e^{-pi*i*j/p}
                      = (-1)^j * e^{-pi*i*j/p}

    So mu_j = omega^j * (1 - omega^{jm}) / (1 - omega^j)
            = omega^j * (1 - (-1)^j * e^{-pi*i*j/p}) / (1 - omega^j)

    For j = 1,...,m (all positive):
    |mu_j| = |sin(pi*j*m/p)| / |sin(pi*j/p)|
           = |sin(pi*j*(p-1)/(2p))| / |sin(pi*j/p)|

    S_I(k) = sum_{j=1}^{p-1} mu_j^k = 2*Re(sum_{j=1}^m mu_j^k)
    

  p=7:
    S_I(k=3) = 15
    S_I(k=5) = -103
    S_I(k=7) = 578
    S_I(k=9) = -2631

  p=11:
    S_I(k=3) = 40
    S_I(k=5) = -705
    S_I(k=7) = 11118
    S_I(k=9) = -156506

  p=19:
    S_I(k=3) = 126
    S_I(k=5) = -6609
    S_I(k=7) = 326625
    S_I(k=9) = -14815422

======================================================================
Section 3: Newton's identity approach — express S_I via symmetric functions
======================================================================
  IDENTITY: sum_{j=0}^{p-1} mu_j^k = p * N_k(p)
  where N_k(p) = #{(s_1,...,s_k) in {1,...,m}^k : sum = 0 mod p}
  So S_I(k) = p * N_k(p) - m^k

  p=7, k=3: N_k=6, p*N_k=42, m^k=27, S_I=p*N_k-m^k=15, direct=15, match=True
  p=7, k=5: N_k=20, p*N_k=140, m^k=243, S_I=p*N_k-m^k=-103, direct=-103, match=True
  p=11, k=3: N_k=15, p*N_k=165, m^k=125, S_I=p*N_k-m^k=40, direct=40, match=True
  p=11, k=5: N_k=220, p*N_k=2420, m^k=3125, S_I=p*N_k-m^k=-705, direct=-705, match=True

======================================================================
Section 4: Paley trace as counting problem
======================================================================
  S_P(k) = p * M_k(p) - m^k
  where M_k(p) = #{(s_1,...,s_k) in QR^k : sum = 0 mod p}
  S_I(k) = p * N_k(p) - m^k
  where N_k(p) = #{(s_1,...,s_k) in {1,...,m}^k : sum = 0 mod p}

  Delta_k = S_P - S_I = p * (M_k - N_k)
  sign(Delta_k) = sign(M_k - N_k)

  THE TRACE ALTERNATION REDUCES TO:
  M_k > N_k when k = 1 mod 4 (more QR solutions)
  M_k < N_k when k = 3 mod 4 (more interval solutions)

  p=7, QR=[1, 2, 4], INT=[1, 2, 3]:
    k=3: M_k=6, N_k=6, M_k-N_k=0, p*(M_k-N_k)=0, k%4=3
    k=5: M_k=30, N_k=20, M_k-N_k=10, p*(M_k-N_k)=70, k%4=1

  p=11, QR=[1, 3, 4, 5, 9], INT=[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]:
    k=3: M_k=15, N_k=15, M_k-N_k=0, p*(M_k-N_k)=0, k%4=3
    k=5: M_k=270, N_k=220, M_k-N_k=50, p*(M_k-N_k)=550, k%4=1

======================================================================
Section 5: Connection to Weil sums and Jacobi sums
======================================================================

    M_k(p) = #{(s_1,...,s_k) in QR^k : sum = 0 mod p}

    This is a WEIL SUM problem! The number of solutions to
    x_1 + ... + x_k = 0 over F_p with each x_i a quadratic residue
    (or zero, but we exclude zero).

    By standard character sum theory:
    M_k = (1/p) * sum_{t=0}^{p-1} (sum_{s in QR} omega^{ts})^k
        = m^k/p + (1/p) * sum_{t=1}^{p-1} ((chi(t)*g - 1)/2)^k
        = m^k/p + S_P(k)/p + ... wait, that's circular.

    Actually: p * M_k = sum_{t=0}^{p-1} lambda_t^k where lambda_t = sum_{s in QR} omega^{ts}
    = m^k + S_P(k)  <-- which is just the trace formula again.

    Similarly: p * N_k = m^k + S_I(k).

    So M_k - N_k = (S_P - S_I)/p = Delta_k/p.

    The question "why does Delta_k alternate?" is equivalent to:
    "Why does QR have more k-sum-zero solutions than {1,...,m} at k=1 mod 4?"

    This is a DEEP question about the additive structure of QR vs intervals.
    

